es © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Strathbogie was born in 1274, in Cromartyshire, Scotland, her father, Alexander de Balliol of Cavers, was 32 and her mother, Isabelle De Dover of Chilham, was 27. She married Iain John MacKenzie 2nd Laird of Kintail before 1294, in Ross-shire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1328, in her hometown, at the age of 54, and was buried in Cromartyshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1274–1328":"1274–1328","1271–1312":"1271–1312","1273–1327":"1273–1327","1275–1290":"1275–1290","1290–1357":"1290–1357","1270–1328":"1270–1328","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1247–1292":"1247–1292","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1273":"1273","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1247":"1247","1346":"1346","1357":"1357","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","before 1294":"enne 1294","18 March 1292":"18. märts 1292","1328":"1328","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kintail, Ross & Cromarty, Scotland":"Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland","Ross-shire, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Scotland","Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1274–1328":"1274–1328","1271–1312":"1271–1312","1273–1327":"1273–1327","1275–1290":"1275–1290","1290–1357":"1290–1357","1270–1328":"1270–1328","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1247–1292":"1247–1292","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1273":"1273","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1247":"1247","1346":"1346","1357":"1357","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","before 1294":"ennen vuotta 1294","18 March 1292":"18. maaliskuuta 1292","1328":"1328","Cromar